4. 

(i) Show that $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty}\left(1+\frac{1}{2}+\ldots+\frac{1}{n}\right)=\infty$;

(ii) Prove that if $I \in \mathbb{R} \cup\{-\infty, \infty\}$, then there exists a sequence $\left(s_{n}\right)_{n \geq 1}$ with $s_{n} \in\{-1,1\}$ for any $n \in \mathbb{N}^{*}$ such that $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty}\left(\frac{s_{1}}{1}+\frac{s_{2}}{2}+\ldots+\frac{s_{n}}{n}\right)=1$.

## NOTE

- All problems are mandatory;
- Each problem is worth 7 points;
- No points are awarded by default;
- The actual working time is 3 hours from the moment the problems are received.


